metadata.name: Asemic writing #3
metadata.description:
This piece is an expanse on my piece for Genuary 2023 "Asemic".

Amidst the cacophony of our mundane language, a new form of expression arises. Each stroke of ink, each fluid line, each curve and shape, has its own unique voice. Breathing life into the seemingly meaningless, each output is its own language, with its own message for us to interpret and read as we see it. All set on a rich paperlike generated texture.

Asemic writing is a visual form of expression that combines elements of writing and art. It transcends traditional linguistic boundaries, using fluid lines, shapes, and curves to suggest meaning and emotion.

Primary Giving
20% Girls Who Code

Interactions:
T = Toggle background textures
S = Save image
R = Replay writing

metadata.name: La Invernada #75
metadata.description:
This project is about my mother's lifestyle. Her work is breeding and herding goats, cows and horses.
She lives a cyclical life marked by two major stages during her livestock year: "La Veranada" and "La Invernada". My last work was about "La Veranada", this work is about "La Invernada", I hope you enjoy it.
Time in the life of a criancero is cyclical. Everything comes and goes, and comes back and comes back. Nature, so present, so in connection with the man and woman who inhabit it, marks the times perhaps like no other place.
 The succession of the seasons, the weather, the buds and "La Invernada", the sowing, the pastures, the harvest and the snows.
"La Invernada" is the place during what we could call the long winter, that is, from April to November.
"La Invernada" is down in the plains, in the pampas, in accessible places, where it is easy to supply forage to the goats that calve between October and November.
The "Criancero" rides a horse every day and, accompanied by his dogs, goes to "watch" the goats. They distinguish them in the distance. Every day is the same and different at the same time. Caring for, watching over and keeping the goats healthy and safe.
"El puesto" is their home. In the stall they use the water from the river, which they draw with a water pump, for their hygiene. Water for consumption is brought in jerry cans from "Vertientes", located about 10 km away.
 The hens roam freely throughout the day, when night comes some go to sleep in the "gallinero" and others simply sleep on small plants.
As you can see, life here is simple, solitary and with a lot of work.
I want to thank all those who have taken the trouble to read the story. I hope you liked it.
You can find real photos and videos of "La Invernada" on my twitter profile.

Features:
10 Color Palettes.
10 types of Animal pen.
Various types of chickens.
14 types of herbs.
10 types of flowerpot.
4 types of trees.
7 types of rivers.
The barn has 4 sizes.
The moon has a very varied range of x and y positions.
6% chance of getting snowy weather in the piece.


Press "S" in live mode to save the 2600 x 3000 image.
Note that the algorithm may take some time to run.

metadata.name: Aging and Forgotten #28
metadata.description:
"Aging and Forgotten" is my tribute to the transience of technology and life. In this exhibit, I bring together a collection of discarded technological devices and symbols of aging and death, such as skulls and bones. My goal is to create a powerful commentary on the impermanence of all things and the parallel between the aging of technology and the aging of people. Through the combination of technology and the human, I invite viewers to reflect on their own experiences of aging, loss, and the passage of time. With "Aging and Forgotten," I aim to challenge viewers to consider the impact of our rapidly advancing technology and the ultimate fate of all things, both human and technological.

- look for the gold mode
- press p to export png
- press s to export svg

metadata.name: Flashy Dendrites v1.0 #11
metadata.description:
I've been playing with noise, chaos, color palettes and growth algorithms. While many of these are pretty, I expect that a few will be exceptionally so... thus I'm releasing 1000 randomly into the wild, hoping that someone finds beauty and serenity in the math that I'm using behind the scenes. All elements are algorithmically generated without me knowing anything about what you're going to get! 

All proceeds will be shared with Girls Who Code and THREE.js.

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

With the keyboard:

Keys "," and "." (i.e. "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed

Press "a" to change the lighting angles.

metadata.name: Wood Generation v1.0 #9
metadata.description:
This entire project will be free for all to mint until it is gone. I'm exploring the idea of creating simulated wood of many different types, colors, and grains. The goal is to allow generation of "boards" which look like they are separate cuts from the same tree. Thus the grain from one must be related to the next but must not be identical...

In this experiment, I slice 9 boards and line them up left-to-right to see the similarities. The features will list the approximate parameters driving the generator.

If the experiment is successful, the code will be able to make as many slices needed, at any thickness, in any direction (across or with the grain, or at any angle).

Enjoy! Feel free to look me up on Discord (Vroomcrds#4688) and DM me if you have questions or suggestions!

All secondary revenues will be shared equally with the minter, THREE.js and Girls Who Code.

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #125
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Mooncakes: Happy Mid Autumn Festival 2022 #465
metadata.description:
To celebrate the Moon Festival with Mooncakes, we have created a quest to introduce everyone to fxhash. As part of that quest on mooncakes.fun, users are encouraged to mint this generative token.

This is a layered image composition using the Mooncakes site images on a 1920x1080 canvas. The image elements are randomly assigned position, scale, tint, and blur according to a ruleset which generates a Mid Autumn Festival scene made up of: Moon, Clouds, Stars, Lanterns, and Lotuses.

Special filters, shapes and colors are included as rare features, as well as a couple of surprises.
